---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Grants Management Portal — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped a federal government grants programme replace email-based PDF applications and printed assessment stacks with a digital portal — processing 40% more applications with the same team and cutting FOI response time from 25 days to 7 days.',
  industry: 'Government',
  tags: ['React', 'FastAPI', 'PostgreSQL', 'DocuSign', 'PDF Parsing Pipeline'],
  title: 'Grants Management Portal',
  summary: 'A federal government grants programme managing $45M in annual grants across three rounds was receiving up to 1,200 applications per round by email as PDF attachments, assessing them from printed stacks, and tracking decisions in Excel. We built a digital portal that processed 40% more applications with the same six-person assessment team, captured every conflict of interest declaration, and got FOI response time under a week.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Grants portal applicant dashboard showing round status and application progress, alongside the assessor interface with scorecard, conflict of interest declaration panel and assessment pipeline overview',

  clientOverview: 'A federal government grants programme focused on regional development, administered by a small team within a government department and overseen by a programme board with external representation. The programme distributes $45 million annually across three funding rounds, with grants ranging from $50,000 to $2 million to regional organisations, local governments, and community groups. The programme operates under the Public Governance, Performance and Accountability Act 2013 (PGPA Act), which imposes specific obligations around grant administration including probity, documentation and reporting.',
  clientSize: '6 assessment staff, programme board of 9, ~800-1,200 applications per round',
  clientLocation: 'Canberra, ACT (programme administration)',

  pullQuote: 'A FOI request used to mean someone on my team spending a week going through their email. Now it means four minutes generating a report. I can\'t overstate how much that has changed things for us — legally and practically.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Programme Director',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Federal Government Grants Programme',

  challenge: [
    'The programme had grown steadily since its establishment, and its administrative processes had not kept pace. What had been manageable when the programme received 200 applications per round was strained at 800 and close to breaking at 1,200. The core problem was that every part of the process — application submission, assessor assignment, scoring, communication with applicants, and reporting — relied on manual human steps rather than structured digital workflows, and each step was a potential failure point.',
    'Applications arrived by email as PDF attachments. A programme officer downloaded each attachment, renamed it to a standard format, saved it to a shared network drive in the relevant round folder, and created a row in an Excel tracker. For a round with 1,000 applications, this intake process alone took the equivalent of one full-time staff member\'s time for the first two weeks of the assessment window. Applications that arrived with missing information — an incomplete form, a missing attachment, an eligibility gap — had to be individually identified, and a follow-up email sent to the applicant. Whether the applicant had responded and whether their response had resolved the issue was tracked through a combination of email folder labels and notes in the Excel spreadsheet.',
    'Assessment happened from printed document packs. The programme officer printed each application — typically 8 to 15 pages — collated it with a printed scorecard, and delivered packs to each assessor. Six assessors, each assessing a subset of applications from a given round, worked from physical folders. Completed scorecards were collected, the scores entered into the Excel tracker, and weighted totals calculated. The assessment process produced no electronic record of the assessor\'s analysis — only a numerical score and a summary comment that the programme officer transcribed from the paper form.',
    'The conflict of interest process was the programme\'s most significant probity risk. Under the PGPA Act and the Commonwealth Grants Rules and Guidelines (CGRGs), assessors must declare any conflicts of interest before assessing applications and must be excluded from any application where a conflict exists. The programme\'s practice was to email assessors a conflict of interest declaration form at the start of each round and ask them to return it. The form was a Word document. Whether every assessor had returned a declaration, and whether declared conflicts had resulted in the correct reassignment of applications, was tracked in a separate spreadsheet column. There was no systematic check. On one occasion, identified during an internal audit, an assessor had assessed two applications where a conflict existed because the conflict declaration had not been received and the programme officer had not noticed the gap.',
    'Reporting to the Department under the PGPA Act\'s performance reporting requirements required compiling application statistics, assessment outcomes, funding ratios by region and organisation type, and time-to-decision metrics. This compilation took three weeks at the end of each round, drawing from the Excel tracker, the email records, the programme officer\'s notes, and direct follow-up with assessors to fill gaps. The data quality was uneven — the three-week timeline was partly genuine compilation time and partly the time needed to identify and resolve inconsistencies in the underlying records.',
    'Freedom of Information requests were the most acutely stressful administrative challenge. The Freedom of Information Act 1982 (Cth) requires agencies to respond to FOI requests within 30 days, with extension provisions that apply in defined circumstances. Requests related to the grants programme — typically from unsuccessful applicants or journalists — required producing the application documents, the assessors\' scorecards, the conflict of interest declarations, and any correspondence between the programme and the applicant. Because none of this material was held in a structured system, producing it required manual email searches, network drive archaeology, and physical document retrieval. The programme had averaged 25 days on FOI responses, consistently close to the statutory limit.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The engagement came through a formal Request for Tender process. The programme had approached the digital marketplace used for government technology procurement and received responses from eleven vendors. The evaluation criteria were explicit: probity and audit capability weighted at 30% (highest single criterion), followed by technical approach at 25%, team experience with government systems at 20%, price at 15%, and transition risk at 10%.',
    'Our submission was distinguished by two things. First, we proposed an architecture in which the FOI compliance capability was the central design constraint, not a reporting feature — an approach we described as "audit-first design." Every other workflow in the system would generate the records needed to answer an FOI request as a natural by-product of operation, rather than requiring those records to be assembled after the fact. Second, our prior experience with the PGPA Act\'s grants administration requirements — we referenced the Commonwealth Grants Rules and Guidelines specifically and described how our proposed workflow enforced CGR compliance procedurally rather than relying on staff knowledge — was noted by the evaluation panel as the most detailed policy understanding of any submission.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'The programme\'s obligations under the CGRGs shaped our design from the beginning. The CGRGs require that grant decisions are based on merit assessment against published criteria, that conflicts of interest are identified and managed, that records are kept sufficient to allow the Australian National Audit Office (ANAO) to examine the programme, and that reporting against programme outcomes occurs. Each of these obligations became a system design requirement.',
    'We spent two weeks in discovery with the programme team, working through every stage of the existing process in detail. We walked through a complete historical round — from the opening of applications to the announcement of funding decisions — using real documents (appropriately de-identified) to trace the information flows and identify where the current process was creating compliance risk. The conflict of interest process was identified in the first day as the highest-risk area. The absence of a systematic check between declarations and assessor assignments was a probity exposure that the programme director was acutely aware of.',
    'We engaged the department\'s legal team for a two-hour session specifically about the FOI implications of the proposed system design. The key questions were: what records needed to be retained, for how long, and in what form to be disclosable under FOI? The answers shaped several specific design decisions — in particular, the decision to retain all intermediate versions of assessment scorecards (because if an assessor revised a score, both the original and the revision needed to be disclosable), and the decision to store all applicant correspondence as structured records in the database rather than as email threads.',
    'The applicant experience was a more significant design consideration than we had initially anticipated. The programme funds regional organisations including small local councils, community groups and not-for-profit associations — organisations that often do not have sophisticated digital capability. The application interface had to be accessible on older browsers, work reliably on rural internet connections, support partial completion and save-and-resume, and provide clear guidance without requiring the applicant to contact the programme team for help. We ran usability testing with five external participants — two from small regional councils, one from a community organisation, one from a regional business, one from a university extension office — before finalising the application form design.',
    'The PDF parsing pipeline was a specific technical requirement that emerged from the discovery process. The programme received applications as PDFs from applicants who had downloaded the form, completed it in Adobe Acrobat or printed and scanned it, and emailed it in. For the transition period — when the new portal was live for the current round but historical applications were still being assessed — we needed to be able to import historical PDF applications into the portal for consistent record-keeping. We built a PDF parsing pipeline that extracted form field data from digital PDFs and flagged scanned PDFs for manual data entry, processing approximately 2,400 historical applications in the three weeks before the first live round.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The portal has three distinct user interfaces: an applicant-facing portal for submitting and tracking applications, an assessor interface for conflict declarations and scoring, and an administration interface for programme staff managing the full round lifecycle.',
    'The applicant portal is a multi-step form builder with save-and-resume functionality. Applicants create an account, complete their organisation profile once (which pre-populates subsequent round applications), and submit their application through a guided form aligned to the round\'s published assessment criteria. Supporting documents are uploaded directly — the portal accepts PDF, Word, Excel and image formats, with virus scanning on upload. Applicants can save a draft and return to it across multiple sessions. Once submitted, the application is locked for editing, and the applicant can view its status (submitted, under review, further information requested, outcome notified) from their dashboard. All correspondence from the programme team is sent through the portal and retained against the application record.',
    'The conflict of interest management system is the platform\'s most probity-critical component. At the start of each round, assessors log into their interface and are presented with the full list of applications assigned to that round, grouped by the applicant organisation. For each application, the assessor declares whether a conflict exists, what the nature of the conflict is (financial interest, personal relationship, prior professional relationship), and — if a conflict exists — is automatically excluded from that application before they can see any assessment content. The system will not permit an assessor to access an application\'s assessment materials until their conflict declaration for that application is confirmed. The declarations are recorded with timestamps and cannot be retroactively modified — an assessor who declares no conflict and later recalls a relationship must lodge a supplementary declaration, which is retained alongside the original. The programme team sees a real-time conflict matrix showing declaration status for every assessor-application pairing.',
    'Assessment scorecards are structured digital forms aligned to the programme\'s published assessment criteria. Each criterion has a numerical score field, a qualitative comment field, and a recommendation field. Assessors complete scorecards on screen; draft scores are auto-saved every 30 seconds. When an assessor marks their scorecard as complete, it is submitted for programme staff review — the assessor can no longer edit it without the programme team re-opening it, which creates a versioned record if changes are needed. The programme staff aggregation view shows all submitted scores by application and by criterion, calculates weighted totals automatically, and highlights applications where assessor scores diverge significantly — a feature the programme director described as "exactly what I needed to identify applications that needed a second look."',
    'Communication with applicants is managed entirely through the portal. Programme staff can send requests for further information, eligibility queries or outcome notifications through the interface; all of these are logged against the application record with timestamps. Applicants receive email notifications linking them to the portal to respond. Responses arrive in the portal and are logged against the application. The email thread between programme and applicant is replaced by a structured correspondence record — every message attributed to an author, timestamped, and attached to the application.',
    'The reporting dashboard generates programme performance reports automatically. Real-time metrics include applications received, eligibility rate, applications under assessment, average time in each assessment stage, and funding ratios by region, organisation type, and grant amount. At round close, the reporting dashboard generates the full departmental submission report — aligned to the PGPA Act performance reporting framework — as a formatted PDF. The report that previously took three weeks to compile now takes approximately 20 minutes to generate and review.',
    'FOI response capability is built as a dedicated feature rather than an export function. For any application, any correspondence, any assessment record or any conflict declaration, an authorised programme officer can generate a full documentary history. The FOI response generator allows the officer to select the specific records responsive to a request, apply standard exemption markers to any material covered by an FOI Act exemption (such as third-party business information or deliberative matter), and produce a redacted PDF bundle ready for disclosure. The process that previously took a week of manual email archaeology now takes an afternoon.',
    'DocuSign handles conflict of interest declarations for programme board members, whose declarations require a higher-formality signature than the logged declarations made by assessment staff. Board member declarations are generated as PDF forms, sent via DocuSign for signature, and the completed declaration is stored against the relevant round record with the DocuSign audit trail attached.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'The implementation timeline was driven by the programme\'s round schedule. Round 1 of the pilot year was already in progress when the portal went live — we used it as a parallel-run round, with the portal handling the intake and records side while assessment still happened partially through the old process. Round 2 was the first fully portal-managed round, with all stages from application through to notification handled through the system.',
    'The application import from historical rounds — approximately 2,400 applications from the three most recent rounds — was completed over a three-week period. The PDF parsing pipeline successfully extracted structured data from approximately 78% of historical applications; the remaining 22% (primarily scanned PDFs and forms completed in older versions of Acrobat) required manual data entry by the programme team. We had estimated 20% would require manual entry; the actual figure was marginally higher due to the prevalence of scanned applications from smaller regional organisations.',
    'Assessor onboarding required individual sessions. Six assessors, with varying degrees of digital confidence, needed to understand both the practical mechanics of the platform and the probity significance of the conflict of interest declaration process. We ran one-hour individual onboarding sessions for each assessor, and the programme director sent a formal communication to all assessors before the first portal-managed round explaining the change to the conflict declaration process and its legal basis. Making the legal basis explicit — that the CGRGs require documented conflict management — was important for assessor buy-in, particularly for external assessors who had not previously worked in a structured compliance framework.',
    'We remained embedded with the programme team through the first fully portal-managed round. One developer was available via direct messaging throughout the assessment window, and we held two check-in calls per week with the programme officer. The main issues that arose during the first live round were a batch email notification failure (resolved within two hours of identification) and a question about how to handle an application submitted minutes before the round deadline — which turned out to be a policy question rather than a technical one, and was resolved by the programme director on the correct basis.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'The conflict of interest declaration system surfaced a policy question we had not anticipated: what constitutes a conflict of interest for the purposes of the programme? The system required assessors to classify the type of conflict, but the classification categories we had proposed based on standard public sector guidance turned out to be inadequate for some of the relationships that assessors encountered. In one case, an assessor was unsure whether a past supervisory relationship with an applicant\'s CEO — which had ended four years previously — required declaration. There was no clear policy answer. The programme director made a decision in the moment. We subsequently helped the programme team draft clearer conflict of interest guidance, but this was programme policy work that fell outside our original scope.',
    'The PDF parsing pipeline was less accurate on complex form layouts than our initial testing had suggested. We had tested on a representative sample of 50 historical applications; the full corpus of 2,400 included some form versions that had been modified over the programme\'s history, producing layouts the parser had not encountered. We improved the parser iteratively during the import phase, but the 22% manual entry rate was higher than the 15% we had projected. For future projects involving document digitisation, we would recommend a larger and more stratified test sample before estimating manual effort.',
    'Applicant support calls to the programme team increased in the first two weeks after the portal went live. Applicants who had submitted applications by email for several previous rounds found the new process unfamiliar, and the programme received more queries than it had budgeted for. We responded by adding a contextual help text to every section of the application form, a "frequently asked questions" panel that appeared on the application page for the first time a user visited it, and a screen-recording walkthrough video linked from the portal home page. These additions were not in the original scope but were built within a week of the issue being identified.',
    'The weighted scoring aggregation — the formula for calculating the combined assessor score for each application — turned out to require more iteration than we had anticipated. The programme\'s assessment criteria had historical numerical weights, but when the first automated aggregations were generated, the programme director identified that some applications were being ranked differently than the manual Excel-based process had ranked them. Investigation revealed a rounding difference in how the Excel formula and our scoring engine handled fractional scores. The difference was small in absolute terms but affected rankings for a small number of applications near scoring thresholds. We corrected the calculation and re-ran the aggregation. The lesson: replicate legacy calculation logic exactly when transitioning scoring systems, even if a more mathematically elegant approach seems preferable.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'Following the first full year of portal operation, the programme asked us to add an outcome tracking module — a structured mechanism for funded organisations to report on their grant milestones and expenditure. Currently, progress reporting arrives by email, which creates the same archiving and tracking problems the portal was designed to solve for applications. The outcome module follows the same portal design pattern: structured forms, save-and-resume, correspondence tracked against the funding record.',
    'The programme board has discussed whether the portal could be extended to manage other aspects of programme governance — board meeting papers, programme evaluation documentation, ministerial briefings. This would be a significant scope extension, and the programme director has appropriately separated it from the immediate post-launch roadmap. We have provided an architecture note on how such an extension could be built without requiring changes to the core grant management functionality.',
    'The portal\'s success has been noted in the Australian National Audit Office\'s cross-programme grant administration guidance, which references the programme\'s conflict of interest management system as an example of good practice. This recognition was entirely driven by the programme team\'s commitment to probity — our role was to build the system that made their existing commitment mechanically enforceable rather than dependent on individual vigilance.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'Processing 40% more applications with the same six-person team is a meaningful efficiency gain, but the number that matters most to the programme director is the FOI response time: from 25 days average to 7 days. That shift reflects something more fundamental than efficiency — it reflects a programme that now has complete, structured records of every decision it makes, and can demonstrate that it administered public money in accordance with the Commonwealth Grants Rules and Guidelines. In a programme that exists to distribute $45 million of public funding each year, that accountability infrastructure is not an overhead. It is the point.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '40%', label: 'More applications processed per round', context: 'From approximately 800 to 1,120 applications per round with the same 6-person assessment team' },
    { value: '2.8 hrs', label: 'Assessment time per application', context: 'Down from 4.2 hours under the paper-based process; total capacity increase ~1,400 staff hours per round' },
    { value: '100%', label: 'Conflict of interest declarations captured', context: 'For every assessor-application pairing; previously informal and acknowledged as inconsistent in internal audits' },
    { value: 'Same day', label: 'Departmental reporting generation', context: 'End-of-round programme performance report generated automatically; previously 3 weeks of manual compilation' },
    { value: '81%', label: 'Reduction in applicant status enquiry calls', context: 'Real-time application status visible in the portal eliminated the majority of inbound status queries' },
    { value: '7 days', label: 'Average FOI response time', context: 'Down from 25 days average; well within the 30-day limit under the Freedom of Information Act 1982 (Cth)' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'React', reason: 'Three distinct user interfaces — applicant portal, assessor interface and administration dashboard — with shared component library' },
    { name: 'FastAPI', reason: 'Python backend for its async performance under concurrent assessment loads and clean integration with the PDF parsing pipeline' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Relational structure for the complex application, assessment, conflict declaration and correspondence data model' },
    { name: 'AWS (EC2 + RDS + S3)', reason: 'Canberra-region hosting for data sovereignty; S3 for application document storage with encryption at rest and immutable versioning' },
    { name: 'DocuSign', reason: 'Formal conflict of interest declarations for programme board members requiring legally compliant digital signatures' },
    { name: 'PDF Parsing Pipeline', reason: 'Automated data extraction from historical PDF applications for the data migration; structured field extraction with manual fallback' },
    { name: 'Role-Based Access Control', reason: 'Granular access model separating applicant, assessor, programme staff and administrator views with application-level isolation for assessors' },
    { name: 'Automated Status Emails (SES)', reason: 'Transactional notifications to applicants on status changes, with all correspondence retained as structured records in the portal' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
